e question of justice in a nonlegal, nonmoral register by understanding it in terms of poetic measure. Focusing on Hölderlin's and Heidegger's readings of pre-Socratic philosophy and Greek tragedy, as well as on Celan's reading of Kabbalah, he frames the problem of poetic justice against the trauma of German destruction in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHeidegger, Martin, -- 1889-1976. 0aHölderlin, Friedrich, -- 1770-1843. 0aJustice. 4aGeneral Interest : Poetry. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Heidegger. 4aPhilosophy : Hermeneutics. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438445823423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438445823/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles